{% import "product-components.njk" as pc %}
<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Guards</strong> standardizes <strong>guarding a region's lifecycle against a predicate</strong>.
    A <em>guard</em> is a policy attached to a region — the document, a route, a modal, a panel, an element —
    that is evaluated at a lifecycle event of that region, and whose <em>deny-branch</em> resolves to a
    member-specific outcome. The region is scale-invariant: the document is the outermost region; routes,
    modals, and elements are inner regions of the same shape.
  </p>
  <p>
    The predicate is never baked into the guarded surface — it is resolved through a swappable
    <strong>guard provider</strong>: a native-first default ships, the project selects or overrides it, and
    custom providers plug in. Swap one policy engine for another (an authorization engine like CASL/OpenFGA,
    a dirty-state tracker) and the guarded surface is untouched. <strong>The provider contract is the only
    lock</strong> — Web Guards fixes the seam (region + event + predicate + provider) and nothing about the
    mechanism. Each member owns its own deny-outcome family; those are <em>not</em> unified.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(5, 150, 105, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #047857; font-size: 1rem;">The problem it solves</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      Two surfaces that look unrelated — "confirm before leaving a dirty form" and "hide a route unless the
      user is an admin" — are the same machine: <strong>a predicate, attached to a region, evaluated at a
      lifecycle event, resolved by a provider</strong>. Today every framework re-invents that machine per
      surface (route guards, render gates, <code>beforeunload</code> handlers) and bakes the policy into each
      one. Web Guards extracts the one reusable seam so the policy is provider-resolved and members differ
      only in <em>when</em> they fire and <em>what their deny-branch does</em>.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

