{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-guard"') }}
  <h3 id="how-it-works">Guard Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    A guarded surface never bundles a policy. It identifies its <strong>region</strong>, hooks the
    cancelable <strong>lifecycle event</strong>, resolves the application's <strong>guard provider</strong>
    through the injector chain, and asks it for a decision. The deny-branch is the member's own — the
    protocol fixes only the seam.
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// The seam — the ONLY lock. A guard provider answers "may this region transition?"
interface CustomGuardProvider {
  // Async by default: an authz provider crosses a trust boundary (server round-trip).
  evaluate(region: GuardRegion, event: GuardEvent, context: GuardContext): Promise<GuardDecision>;
  // Revocable: a decision can change (token expiry, ability change). Optional invalidation signal.
  subscribe?(region: GuardRegion, onInvalidate: () => void): Cleanup;
}

interface GuardDecision {
  allow: boolean;
  // The deny REASON lives behind the provider — forbid(403) vs cloak(404) is a SECURITY call
  // (whether to reveal the resource exists), not a UX preference. The member maps reason → outcome.
  reason?: 'unauthorized' | 'forbidden' | 'not-found' | 'precondition' | 'loss-of-state' | string;
}

// 1. The application registers ONE provider (native-first default; project overrides it).
customGuards.define('authz', new CASLGuardProvider(ability));

injector Application {
  provide { guard: 'authz' } to '@web-guards';   // every descendant resolves this provider
}

// 2. A member surface delegates — it owns only its deny-branch, never the policy.
const provider = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(el, 'customGuards');
const decision = await provider.evaluate(region, 'enter', context);
if (!decision.allow) entryGuard.deny(decision.reason);   // member maps reason → hide|redirect|forbid|cloak
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>One contract:</strong> <code>CustomGuardProvider</code> — <code>evaluate(region, event, context): Promise&lt;GuardDecision&gt;</code> — is satisfied by the native default and every plugged engine alike.</li>
    <li><strong>One registry:</strong> <code>CustomGuardRegistry</code> (<code>window.customGuards</code>) holds the named providers; the project selects/overrides via the injector chain (defaults live in the platform config a project extends, shipped as flavors — the tool itself carries no default).</li>
    <li><strong>Hook the cancelable trigger, not the removal:</strong> raw <code>el.remove()</code> / <code>disconnectedCallback</code> is not cancelable. The guard intercepts the intentful dismissal (close button, route change, <code>beforeunload</code>). Imperative teardown that bypasses a guardable trigger cannot be caught — this is a stated boundary of the contract.</li>
    <li><strong>Native-first default:</strong> for exit, the default wires the cancelable browser primitives (<code>beforeunload</code>, Navigation API <code>intercept</code>, <code>dialog</code> <code>cancel</code>). For access there is <em>no</em> native authorization primitive, so the default provider is permissive and the project supplies a real authz provider.</li>
  </ul>

  <h4 id="provider-trust-boundary" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">The guard provider is not the positioning provider</h4>
  <p style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    Web Guards reuses the <em>pattern</em> of <a href="/projects/webpositioning/">Anchor Positioning</a>'s
    provider (a named registry + injector-resolved contract, native-first), but <strong>not its
    shape</strong>. The positioning provider is synchronous and purely client-side
    (<code>place() &rarr; teardown</code>). A guard provider — especially an authorization one — crosses a
    <strong>trust boundary</strong>, so its contract is materially different:
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>Async</strong> — <code>evaluate()</code> returns a <code>Promise</code>; the decision may require a server round-trip.</li>
    <li><strong>Server-authoritative</strong> — the back-end enforces; the front-end guard is a <em>UX mirror</em>, never the enforcement point. The standard is not to be mistaken for security.</li>
    <li><strong>Revocable / cacheable</strong> — a decision can change after it is made; the optional <code>subscribe()</code> signal lets a guarded surface re-evaluate when the provider invalidates.</li>
  </ul>

  <h4 id="rulings" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Design rulings (the three sub-questions <a href="/backlog/272-guard-protocol-predicate-gated-transitions-and-presence-open/">#272</a> left open)</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>The rendering "Gate" dissolves — it is not a distinct member.</strong> An access gate that
      renders-or-hides on a predicate is just <em>any visibility-bearing construct reading the same guard
      provider</em> — a consumption pattern, not a sibling intent. So the member set is
      <code>{ entry guard, exit guard }</code>; the access case (<a href="/backlog/178-access-control-authorization-gate/">#178</a>)
      is one entry-guard provider consumed by both routing (a transition guard) and rendering (a conditional
      surface), off one authz provider.</li>
    <li><strong>The <code>forbid</code>(403) / <code>cloak</code>(404) enum lives behind the provider</strong>,
      surfaced as <code>GuardDecision.reason</code> — not in the member intent. Whether to reveal that a
      resource exists is a server/security decision; member intents are UX-only and merely <em>map</em> the
      reason to what the user sees.</li>
    <li><strong>The authz provider gets its own contract treatment</strong> (async / server-authoritative /
      revocable), not a verbatim reuse of the positioning provider — see above.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="composition"') }}
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <p>
    Web Guards owns <em>whether a region may transition</em>, not authentication, not the browser's
    capability permissions, and not the policy engine itself — those compose with neighbouring standards:
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>Member intents</strong> — the <a href="/intents/exit-guard/">Exit Guard intent</a> and <a href="/backlog/178-access-control-authorization-gate/">access control (#178)</a> are UX intents built <em>on</em> this protocol; they declare their region, event, and deny-outcome and defer the predicate to a guard provider.</li>
    <li><strong>Web Identity / authentication</strong> — establishes <em>who the user is</em>; the guard provider consumes that identity to decide <em>what they may do</em>. Distinct concern.</li>
    <li><strong>Browser Permissions (webpermissions)</strong> — the native Permissions API (camera, geolocation, notifications) is a different axis; do not conflate app-level authorization with device-capability grants.</li>
    <li><strong>Background Task</strong> — its <code>navigationGuard</code> dimension collapses to referencing the exit-guard member rather than redefining the machinery.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="status"') }}
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Guards is in <strong>concept</strong> phase. The Guard protocol's seam (region + event + predicate +
    provider) is specified here; the two member intents (exit guard, access control) and the native-first
    default provider are the first planned work, on top of this contract.
  </p>
  <h4 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Open Questions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li>Does <code>GuardContext</code> carry the resolved identity, or resolve it lazily inside the provider?</li>
    <li>How does a region express its identity to the provider when it spans both a route and a rendered element (the #178 dual-surface case) — one shared key, or two registrations?</li>
    <li>Default debounce / batching for <code>subscribe()</code> invalidation so a revoked ability doesn't thrash every guarded surface at once.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}
